snippet.textDisplay:
I think you guys should do a revisit video about the Paging File, and it's potential direct link to gaming, I was able to get a repeatable instance on multiple different computers with the very popular GTA V. Where if you have 8gb of ram and no Paging File the game will crash shortly after loading in, but as soon as you enable the Paging File 2000mb or higher it works perfectly fine. 

I found this because I was cleaning up an old HP and it only had 8gb of ram, I loaded GTA V onto it anticipating 8gb would be more then enough, but every time after launching and loading in the game would crash and lock up the whole system, but very occasionally giving me a "No page Guard error" but found no useful information about it online. I thought this to be indicative of a RAM error so I swapped out the ram sticks 4 times, only to have the same error. I reluctantly As a last stitch effort enabled the Paging File anticipating it to have no effect but low and behold the crashes stopped, so I shut off the Paging File and tried again and it crashed just like before. I proceeded to try on 2 other computers I had but just removing ram so I only had 8gb and no Paging File, and the error occured again, on 3 totally different systems with 2 with DDR3 and one with DDR4.
It also just seems to be a topic that's not often touched upon but with today's newer NVME SSD's and PCIE adapter SSD's would a Paging File on one of those be as fast enough to even be comparable to physical ram? 
The last LTT video covering it was 7 years ago, time for a tech upgrade :P
